The name is first recorded in 848 as ''Grenan forda''. It is formed from the [[Old English]] 'gr<U+0113>ne' and 'ford' and means 'place at the green ford'. Greenford was known as '''Great Greenford''' to distinguish it from [[Perivale|Little Greenford]], which is now known as Perivale. The affixes 'Magma' and 'Muche' have also been used to denote the difference.<ref name=mills>{{ cite book | surname=Mills | first=D. | title=Oxford Dictionary of London Place Names | year=2000 | publisher=Oxford}}</ref>

==History==
Greenford is considered to be birthplace of the modern [[organic chemical]] industry {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}, as it was at [[Sir William Henry Perkin|William Perkin's]] chemical factory in North Greenford, by the [[Grand Union Canal]] that the world's first [[aniline]] dye was discovered in March 1856. Perkin called his amazing discovery '[[mauveine]]'. Today there is a [[blue plaque]] marking the spot in Oldfield Lane North, just south of the Black Horse [[Public House]].  The former [[Rockware Glass|Rockware glassworks]] on the canal is commemorated by Rockware Avenue. Greenford formed part of [[Greenford Urban District]] from 1894 to 1926 and was then absorbed by the [[Municipal Borough of Ealing]].

==Economy==
[[Image:Ravenor Park-Greenford Autumn.JPG|thumb|left|Autumn in Greenford, Ravenor Park]]

Significant local businesses include [[British Bakeries]], [[IBM]], [[GlaxoSmithKline]] (GSK, pharmaceutical research and development), [[Panavision]], Panalux, [[Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company|P&O]] (Distribution Centre) and [[Royal Mail]] (Regional distribution centre). [[KBR (company)|KBR]] has an office in Greenford.<ref>"[http://www.kbr.com/locations.aspx Locations]." ''[[KBR (company)|KBR]]''. Retrieved on 13 January 2008.</ref>

==Sport==
The trotting track at Greenford was a pioneer [[speedway]] venue and open meetings were staged 1928<U+2013>1930 {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}. The track would be called a long track now, as it was of the order of half a mile/800 metres per lap. The Trotting Park was situated on what is now Birkbeck Avenue. Just north of the A40 Western Avenue.

